A user types [www.foobar.com](http://www.foobar.com) in the browser.

DNS resolves the domain name and sends the request to the load balancer cluster.

I added a second HAProxy load balancer to avoid having a single point of failure. If one load balancer fails, the other one can continue serving requests.

The load balancers distribute traffic to the web servers.

The web servers run Nginx and are responsible for receiving HTTP requests and serving static content.

I separated the application server from the web servers. The application server is responsible for running the application logic and processing requests.

I also separated the database onto its own server. This improves performance, organization, and makes the infrastructure easier to scale.

By splitting the components, each server has a specific responsibility:

* Load Balancers: distribute traffic
* Web Servers: handle web requests
* Application Server: runs the application code
* Database Server: stores application data

This design is more scalable because each component can be upgraded independently when needed.

The additional server was added to separate services and reduce resource competition between web, application, and database components.

The second load balancer was added to improve availability and reduce the risk of downtime if one load balancer fails
